### Description

`mf-sgd-cuda`: running the program with the crafted binary training file `mfsgd-neg-uv.txt` causes a host-side heap buffer underflow (SIGSEGV) in `grid_problem()` in `src/mf-sgd-cuda/src/sgd.cu`.

### Reproduce

The kernel file `sgd_k128_kernel_hogwild_warp32.h` uses deprecated `__shfl`/`__shfl_down` intrinsics that were removed in CUDA 9; updating them to `__shfl_sync(0xffffffff, ...)`/`__shfl_down_sync(0xffffffff, ...)` allows compilation with CUDA 13.2 without changing semantics.

```diff
--- a/src/mf-sgd-cuda/src/sgd_k128_kernel_hogwild_warp32.h
+++ b/src/mf-sgd-cuda/src/sgd_k128_kernel_hogwild_warp32.h
@@ -38,7 +38,7 @@ __global__ void sgd_k128_kernel_hogwild_warp32_lrate(
         long long origin = (long long)(LCG_random(state+wid)*nnz);
         start_id = origin%nnz;
       }
-      start_id = __shfl(start_id, 0);
+      start_id = __shfl_sync(0xffffffff, start_id, 0);

       for(int i = 0;i < update_vector_size;i++)
       {
@@ -67,12 +67,12 @@ __global__ void sgd_k128_kernel_hogwild_warp32_lrate(
         float tmp_product = tmp_p1*tmp_q1 + tmp_p2*tmp_q2 + tmp_p3*tmp_q3 + tmp_p4*tmp_q4;

         //get dot product.
-        tmp_product += __shfl_down(tmp_product, 16);
-        tmp_product += __shfl_down(tmp_product, 8);
-        tmp_product += __shfl_down(tmp_product, 4);
-        tmp_product += __shfl_down(tmp_product, 2);
-        tmp_product += __shfl_down(tmp_product, 1);
-        tmp_product = __shfl(tmp_product,0);
+        tmp_product += __shfl_down_sync(0xffffffff, tmp_product, 16);
+        tmp_product += __shfl_down_sync(0xffffffff, tmp_product, 8);
+        tmp_product += __shfl_down_sync(0xffffffff, tmp_product, 4);
+        tmp_product += __shfl_down_sync(0xffffffff, tmp_product, 2);
+        tmp_product += __shfl_down_sync(0xffffffff, tmp_product, 1);
+        tmp_product = __shfl_sync(0xffffffff, tmp_product,0);

         float ruv = r - tmp_product;
```

After that fix:

```bash
cd HeCBench/src/mf-sgd-cuda/src
make clean && make ARCH=sm_80 EXTRA_CFLAGS="-lineinfo"
./main ./mfsgd-neg-uv.txt
```

### PoC

[mfsgd-neg-uv.txt](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/29723280/mfsgd-neg-uv.txt)

### Environment

- **CUDA version**: CUDA 13.2
- **GPU**: NVIDIA A30 (sm_80)
- **OS**: Ubuntu 24.04
- **Commit**: 15ff7a0976d493625a4948c299e04654bcfa4ef9

### Relevant Log Snippet

```
k          :80
num_workers:12
u_grid     :1
v_grid     :1
x_grid     :1
y_grid     :1
ux         :1
vy         :1
num_iters  :30
gpu        :0
lambda_p   :0.05000
lambda_q   :0.05000
lrate      :0.00000
alpha      :0.0100
beta       :0.0100
tr_path    :mfsgd-neg-uv.txt
va_path    :
model_path :mfsgd-neg-uv.txt.model
read problem called
prob.nnz = 1
m:1, n:1, nnz:1
time elapsed:0.00110787s


sgd_train called
[1]    680022 segmentation fault  ./main
```

### Root Cause

`grid_problem()` in `sgd.cu` assigns each `mf_node` to a grid cell via:

```cpp
// sgd.cu:314-316
auto get_grid_id = [=](int u, int v)
{
    return ((u/u_seg)*prob->vy + v/v_seg);
};
```

This lambda is applied without validating that `u ∈ [0, m)` or `v ∈ [0, n)`:

```cpp
// sgd.cu:321
int tmp_u = prob->R[i].u;
int tmp_v = prob->R[i].v;
gridSize[get_grid_id(tmp_u, tmp_v)] ++;  // OOB if u or v is negative
```

### Suggested Fix

```diff
--- a/src/mf-sgd-cuda/src/sgd.cu
+++ b/src/mf-sgd-cuda/src/sgd.cu
@@ -319,6 +319,9 @@ void grid_problem(mf_problem* prob)
   for(long long i = 0;i < prob->nnz;i++)
   {
     int tmp_u = prob->R[i].u;
     int tmp_v = prob->R[i].v;
+    if (tmp_u < 0 || tmp_u >= prob->m || tmp_v < 0 || tmp_v >= prob->n)
+      continue; // or report error
     gridSize[get_grid_id(tmp_u, tmp_v)] ++;
```

### Description

`sobel-cuda`: running the program with the crafted BMP file `sobel-sdkbitmap.txt` causes a host-side heap buffer overflow (SIGSEGV) inside `SDKBitMap::load()` in `src/include/SDKBitMap.h`.

### Reproduce

```bash
cd HeCBench/src/sobel-cuda
make clean && make ARCH=sm_80 EXTRA_CFLAGS="-lineinfo"
./main ./sobel-sdkbitmap.txt 1
```

### PoC

[sobel-sdkbitmap.txt](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/29722341/sobel-sdkbitmap.txt)

### Environment

- **CUDA version**: CUDA 13.2
- **GPU**: NVIDIA A30 (sm_80)
- **OS**: Ubuntu 24.04
- **Commit**: 15ff7a0976d493625a4948c299e04654bcfa4ef9

### Relevant Log Snippet

```
[1]    663721 segmentation fault  ./main  1
```

### Root Cause

`SDKBitMap::load()` (in `src/include/SDKBitMap.h`) validates the pixel-data size with a signed integer comparison that overflows for crafted inputs:

```cpp
// SDKBitMap.h:310-315
int sizeBuffer = size - offset;
if (width * height * (bitsPerPixel / 8) != sizeBuffer) {
    printf("This is not a valid bitmap file.\n");
    fclose(fd);
    return;
}
```

The PoC BMP encodes `width = 0x18000020` (402,653,216) and `height = 32` with a pixel data section of 3072 bytes (`sizeBuffer = 3126 - 54 = 3072`). The check `width * height * 3 != sizeBuffer` is evaluated in 32-bit signed arithmetic: `402653216 × 32 × 3 = 38654708736`, which wraps to `3072` — exactly matching `sizeBuffer`. The validation passes despite the values being wildly inconsistent.

Subsequently (in `src/include/SDKBitMap.h:361`):

```cpp
pixels_ = new uchar4[width * height];
// width * height again overflows: (402653216 * 32) mod (2^32) = 1024 elements allocated
```

Only 1024 `uchar4` elements (4096 bytes) are allocated, but the copy loop at `src/include/SDKBitMap.h:389-391` iterates `for (y < 32) { for (x < 402653216) { pixels_[y*width+x] = ... } }`. `pixels_[x]` is written for `x = 0 … 402653215`, far beyond the 1024-entry allocation, causing a **heap buffer overflow**.

### Suggested Fix

```diff
--- a/src/include/SDKBitMap.h
+++ b/src/include/SDKBitMap.h
@@ -308,8 +308,14 @@ class SDKBitMap : public BitMapHeader, public BitMapInfoHeader
           }
           int sizeBuffer = size - offset;
-          if (width * height * (bitsPerPixel / 8) != sizeBuffer) {
+          // Use 64-bit arithmetic to avoid signed overflow on large width/height.
+          if (sizeBuffer < 0 ||
+              (long long)width * height * (bitsPerPixel / 8) != (long long)sizeBuffer) {
             printf("This is not a valid bitmap file.\n");
             fclose(fd);
             return;
           }
+          // Also reject images whose pixel array would overflow int.
+          if ((long long)width * height > (1LL << 28)) {
+            fclose(fd);
+            return;
+          }
```

### Description

`rsmt-cuda`: running the `rsmt-cuda` program with the crafted input file `rsmt-racecheck.txt` will cause a race condition in the `buildMST` and `insertSteinerPoints` kernels.

### Reproduce

```bash
cd HeCBench/src/rsmt-cuda
make clean && make ARCH=sm_80 EXTRA_CFLAGS="-lineinfo"
compute-sanitizer --tool=racecheck ./main ./rsmt-racecheck.txt
```

### PoC

[rsmt-racecheck.txt](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/29075391/rsmt-racecheck.txt)

### Environment

- **CUDA version**: CUDA 13.2
- **GPU**: NVIDIA A30 (sm_80)
- **OS**: Ubuntu 24.04
- **Commit**: f6a9935b5327920d63c917163c75d5d847b6623b

### Relevant Log Snippet

```
========= Warning: Race reported between Read access at void buildMST<(int)24, (int)64>(short, const int *, const int *, edge *, int *)+0xd10 in main.cu:53
=========     and Write access at void buildMST<(int)24, (int)64>(short, const int *, const int *, edge *, int *)+0xe90 in main.cu:60 [24 hazards]
=========
========= Warning: Race reported between Write access at void buildMST<(int)24, (int)64>(short, const int *, const int *, edge *, int *)+0x6c0 in main.cu:26
=========     and Read access at bool insertSteinerPoints<(int)24, (int)64>(short &, int *, int *, const edge *, int *)+0x1e00 in main.cu:134 [12 hazards]
=========
```

### Root Cause

```cpp
// In buildMST kernel
    src = destin[warp][j]; // main.cu:53
    numItems--;
    if (lane == 0) {
      edges[cnt].src = source[warp][j];
      edges[cnt].dst = src;
      dist[j] = dist[numItems];
      source[warp][j] = source[warp][numItems];
      destin[warp][j] = destin[warp][numItems]; // main.cu:60
```

In the `buildMST` kernel, all 32 lanes redundantly read `destin[warp][j]` at `main.cu:53`, but only `lane == 0` overwrites `destin[warp][j]` a few lines later (`main.cu:60`). There was no `__syncwarp()` between that broadcast read and the lane-0-only write, so with independent thread scheduling a fast lane 0 could overwrite the slot before slower lanes finished reading it. This caused the first race condition.

```cpp
// In buildMST kernel
  for (ID i = lane; i < numItems; i += WS) dist[i] = INT_MAX;  // main.cu:26
  for (ID i = lane; i < numItems; i += WS) destin[warp][i] = (ID)(i + 1);
// ...
// In insertSteinerPoints kernel
      if (d1 > 0) {
        const ID e2 = d1 % (MaxPins * 2);
        if (e2 > e1) {
          const ctype d2 = dist[e2]; // main.cu:134
```

In the `insertSteinerPoints` kernel, the last per-lane divergent read of `dist[e2]` (`main.cu:134`) could still be in flight when the next `buildMST` call (in the `do { buildMST(); } while (insertSteinerPoints());` loop) began clobbering `dist[i] = INT_MAX` (`main.cu:26`). This caused the second race condition.

### Suggested Fix

```diff
@@ -52,6 +52,7 @@ void buildMST(const ID num,
     const ID j = mindj[warp] % (MaxPins * 2);
     src = destin[warp][j];
     numItems--;
+    __syncwarp();
     if (lane == 0) {
       edges[cnt].src = source[warp][j];
       edges[cnt].dst = src;
@@ -60,6 +61,7 @@ void buildMST(const ID num,
       destin[warp][j] = destin[warp][numItems];
     }
   }
+  __syncwarp();
 }

 template <int WarpsPerBlock, int PinLimit>
@@ -160,6 +162,7 @@ bool insertSteinerPoints(ID& num,
     num += __popc(bal);
   }

+  __syncwarp();
   return __any_sync(0xffffffff, updated);
 }
```

### Description

`hungarian-cuda`: a race condition occurs in the `min_in_rows_warp_reduce`, `min_in_cols_warp_reduce`, and `min_warp_reduce` kernels, when running the `hungarian-cuda` program.

### Reproduce

```bash
cd HeCBench/src/hungarian-cuda
make clean && make ARCH=sm_80 EXTRA_CFLAGS="-lineinfo"
compute-sanitizer --tool=racecheck ./main output.txt
```

### Environment

- **CUDA version**: CUDA 13.2
- **GPU**: NVIDIA A30 (sm_80)
- **OS**: Ubuntu 24.04
- **Commit**: f6a9935b5327920d63c917163c75d5d847b6623b

### Relevant Log Snippet

```
========= COMPUTE-SANITIZER
========= Warning: Race reported between Write access at min_in_rows_warp_reduce(volatile int *, int)+0x650 in main.cu:146
=========     and Read access at min_in_rows_warp_reduce(volatile int *, int)+0x660 in main.cu:147 [28672 hazards]
=========
========= Warning: Race reported between Write access at min_in_rows_warp_reduce(volatile int *, int)+0x610 in main.cu:145
=========     and Read access at min_in_rows_warp_reduce(volatile int *, int)+0x620 in main.cu:146 [24576 hazards]
=========
========= Warning: Race reported between Write access at min_in_rows_warp_reduce(volatile int *, int)+0x5d0 in main.cu:144
=========     and Read access at min_in_rows_warp_reduce(volatile int *, int)+0x5e0 in main.cu:145 [16384 hazards]
=========
========= Warning: Race reported between Write access at min_in_cols_warp_reduce(volatile int *, int)+0x660 in main.cu:187
=========     and Read access at min_in_cols_warp_reduce(volatile int *, int)+0x670 in main.cu:188 [28672 hazards]
=========
========= Warning: Race reported between Write access at min_in_cols_warp_reduce(volatile int *, int)+0x620 in main.cu:186
=========     and Read access at min_in_cols_warp_reduce(volatile int *, int)+0x630 in main.cu:187 [24576 hazards]
=========
========= Warning: Race reported between Write access at min_in_cols_warp_reduce(volatile int *, int)+0x5e0 in main.cu:185
=========     and Read access at min_in_cols_warp_reduce(volatile int *, int)+0x5f0 in main.cu:186 [16384 hazards]
=========
========= Warning: Race reported between Write access at void min_warp_reduce<(unsigned int)256>(volatile int *, int)+0x5d0 in main.cu:460
=========     and Read access at void min_warp_reduce<(unsigned int)256>(volatile int *, int)+0x5e0 in main.cu:461 [31744 hazards]
=========
========= Warning: Race reported between Write access at void min_warp_reduce<(unsigned int)256>(volatile int *, int)+0x590 in main.cu:459
=========     and Read access at void min_warp_reduce<(unsigned int)256>(volatile int *, int)+0x5a0 in main.cu:460 [30720 hazards]
=========
========= Warning: Race reported between Write access at void min_warp_reduce<(unsigned int)256>(volatile int *, int)+0x550 in main.cu:458
=========     and Read access at void min_warp_reduce<(unsigned int)256>(volatile int *, int)+0x560 in main.cu:459 [28672 hazards]
// ...
```

### Root Cause

`compute-sanitizer`'s `racecheck` tool flags races in the three warp-level shared-memory reductions: `min_in_rows_warp_reduce`, `min_in_cols_warp_reduce`, and the templated `min_warp_reduce`.

Each is the classic "unrolled warp-synchronous reduction" pattern, such as:

```cpp
if (blockSize >= 64) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 32]);
if (blockSize >= 32) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 16]);
// ...
```

This relies on the pre-Volta assumption that all 32 lanes of a warp execute each line in lockstep — i.e. every lane's read completes before any lane's write. Since Volta, Independent Thread Scheduling (ITS) removes that guarantee: lanes can interleave their load/compute/store sequence for the same statement. So one lane's write to `sdata[tid]` can race with another lane's read of `sdata[tid' + offset]` where the index ranges overlap between consecutive reduction steps.

### Suggested Fix

```diff
@@ -142,11 +142,17 @@ const int n_rows_per_block = n / n_blocks_reduction;

 __device__ void min_in_rows_warp_reduce(volatile data* sdata, int tid) {
   if (n_threads_reduction >= 64 && n_rows_per_block < 64) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 32]);
+  __syncwarp();
   if (n_threads_reduction >= 32 && n_rows_per_block < 32) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 16]);
+  __syncwarp();
   if (n_threads_reduction >= 16 && n_rows_per_block < 16) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 8]);
+  __syncwarp();
   if (n_threads_reduction >= 8 && n_rows_per_block < 8) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 4]);
+  __syncwarp();
   if (n_threads_reduction >= 4 && n_rows_per_block < 4) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 2]);
+  __syncwarp();
   if (n_threads_reduction >= 2 && n_rows_per_block < 2) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 1]);
+  __syncwarp();
 }

 __global__ void calc_min_in_rows()
@@ -183,11 +189,17 @@ const int n_cols_per_block = n / n_blocks_reduction;

 __device__ void min_in_cols_warp_reduce(volatile data* sdata, int tid) {
   if (n_threads_reduction >= 64 && n_cols_per_block < 64) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 32]);
+  __syncwarp();
   if (n_threads_reduction >= 32 && n_cols_per_block < 32) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 16]);
+  __syncwarp();
   if (n_threads_reduction >= 16 && n_cols_per_block < 16) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 8]);
+  __syncwarp();
   if (n_threads_reduction >= 8 && n_cols_per_block < 8) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 4]);
+  __syncwarp();
   if (n_threads_reduction >= 4 && n_cols_per_block < 4) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 2]);
+  __syncwarp();
   if (n_threads_reduction >= 2 && n_cols_per_block < 2) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 1]);
+  __syncwarp();
 }

 __global__ void calc_min_in_cols()
@@ -454,11 +466,17 @@ __global__ void step_5b()
 template <unsigned int blockSize>
 __device__ void min_warp_reduce(volatile data* sdata, int tid) {
   if (blockSize >= 64) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 32]);
+  __syncwarp();
   if (blockSize >= 32) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 16]);
+  __syncwarp();
   if (blockSize >= 16) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 8]);
+  __syncwarp();
   if (blockSize >= 8) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 4]);
+  __syncwarp();
   if (blockSize >= 4) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 2]);
+  __syncwarp();
   if (blockSize >= 2) sdata[tid] = min(sdata[tid], sdata[tid + 1]);
+  __syncwarp();
 }
```

### Description

`mis-cuda`: running the `mis-cuda` program with the crafted input file `mis-memcheck.txt` will cause a heap buffer overflow in the `findmins` kernel.

### Reproduce

```bash
cd HeCBench/src/mis-cuda
make clean && make ARCH=sm_80 EXTRA_CFLAGS="-lineinfo"
compute-sanitizer --tool=memcheck ./main ./mis-memcheck.txt 1
```

### PoC

[mis-memcheck.txt](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/29068576/mis-memcheck.txt)

### Environment

- **CUDA version**: CUDA 13.2
- **GPU**: NVIDIA A30 (sm_80)
- **OS**: Ubuntu 24.04
- **Commit**: f6a9935b5327920d63c917163c75d5d847b6623b

### Relevant Log Snippet

```
========= Invalid __global__ read of size 4 bytes
=========     at findmins(int, const int *, const int *, volatile unsigned char *)+0x200 in main.cu:77
=========     by thread (13,0,0) in block (0,0,0)
=========     Access to 0xc7cefdfff94 is out of bounds
=========     and is 108 bytes before the nearest allocation at 0xc7cefe00000 of size 2063872 bytes
=========     Saved host backtrace up to driver entry point at kernel launch time
=========         Host Frame: computeMIS(int, int, int, int const*, int const*, unsigned char*) [0x9b31] in main
=========         Host Frame: main [0x8c04] in main
```

### Root Cause

```cpp
    if (nv & 1) {
        int i = nidx[v];
        while ((i < nidx[v + 1]) && ((nv > nstat[nlist[i]]) || ((nv == nstat[nlist[i]]) && (v > nlist[i])))) { // main.cu:77
            i++;
        }
```

The value of `i` is not checked before using as an index into the `nlist` array (max length of `nlist` is `edges`).

### Suggested Fix

```diff
@@ -59,7 +60,7 @@ static const stattype out = 0;
 /* main computation kernel */

 __global__
-void findmins(const int nodes,
+void findmins(const int nodes, const int edges,
     const int* const __restrict nidx,
     const int* const __restrict nlist,
     volatile stattype* const __restrict nstat)
@@ -74,6 +75,7 @@ void findmins(const int nodes,
       const stattype nv = nstat[v];
       if (nv & 1) {
         int i = nidx[v];
+        assert(i >= 0 && i < edges);
         while ((i < nidx[v + 1]) && ((nv > nstat[nlist[i]]) || ((nv == nstat[nlist[i]]) && (v > nlist[i])))) {
           i++;
         }
@@ -164,7 +166,7 @@ void computeMIS(
   for (int n = 0; n < repeat; n++) {
     init<<<blocks, ThreadsPerBlock>>>(nodes, edges, nidx_d, nstat_d);

-    findmins<<<blocks, ThreadsPerBlock>>>(nodes, nidx_d, nlist_d, nstat_d);
+    findmins<<<blocks, ThreadsPerBlock>>>(nodes, edges, nidx_d, nlist_d, nstat_d);
   }
```

### Description

`cc-cuda`: running the `cc-cuda` program with the crafted input file `cc-memcheck.txt` will cause a heap buffer overflow in the `init` kernel.

### Reproduce

```bash
cd HeCBench/src/cc-cuda
make clean && make ARCH=sm_80 EXTRA_CFLAGS="-lineinfo"
compute-sanitizer --tool=memcheck ./main ./cc-memcheck.txt 1
```

### PoC

[cc-memcheck.txt](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/29065264/cc-memcheck.txt)

### Environment

- **CUDA version**: CUDA 13.2
- **GPU**: NVIDIA A30 (sm_80)
- **OS**: Ubuntu 24.04
- **Commit**: f6a9935b5327920d63c917163c75d5d847b6623b

### Relevant Log Snippet

```
========= Invalid __global__ read of size 4 bytes
=========     at init(int, const int *, const int *, int *)+0x140 in main.cu:73
=========     by thread (13,0,0) in block (0,0,0)
=========     Access to 0x14188bbfff94 is out of bounds
=========     by thread (13,0,0) in block (0,0,0)
=========     Access to 0x14188bbfff94 is out of bounds
=========     and is 108 bytes before the nearest allocation at 0x14188bc00000 of size 4177408 bytes
=========     Saved host backtrace up to driver entry point at kernel launch time
=========         Host Frame: cudaLaunchKernel [0x7dd87] in main
=========         Host Frame: main [0xa57f] in main
```

### Root Cause

```cpp
for (int v = from; v < nodes; v += incr) {
  const int beg = nidx[v];
  const int end = nidx[v + 1];
  int m = v;
  int i = beg;
  while ((m == v) && (i < end)) {
    m = min(m, nlist[i]); // main.cu:73
    i++;
  }
  nstat[v] = m;
}
```

The value of `i` is not checked before using as an index into the `nlist` array (max length of `nlist` is `edges`).

### Suggested Fix

```diff
@@ -57,6 +58,7 @@ static __device__ int topL, posL, topH, posH;

 static __global__ __launch_bounds__(ThreadsPerBlock, 2048 / ThreadsPerBlock)
 void init(const int nodes,
+          const int edges,
           const int* const __restrict__ nidx,
           const int* const __restrict__ nlist,
                 int* const __restrict__ nstat)
@@ -70,9 +72,11 @@ void init(const int nodes,
     int m = v;
     int i = beg;
     while ((m == v) && (i < end)) {
+      assert(i >= 0 && i < edges);
       m = min(m, nlist[i]);
       i++;
     }
+    assert(v >= 0 && v < nodes);
     nstat[v] = m;
   }

@@ -312,7 +316,7 @@ static void computeCC(const int repeat,
   auto start = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();

   for (int n = 0; n < repeat; n++) {
-    init<<<blocks, ThreadsPerBlock>>>(nodes, nidx_d, nlist_d, nstat_d);
+    init<<<blocks, ThreadsPerBlock>>>(nodes, edges, nidx_d, nlist_d, nstat_d);
     compute1<<<blocks, ThreadsPerBlock>>>(nodes, nidx_d, nlist_d, nstat_d, wl_d);
     compute2<<<blocks, ThreadsPerBlock>>>(nodes, nidx_d, nlist_d, nstat_d, wl_d);
     compute3<<<blocks, ThreadsPerBlock>>>(nodes, nidx_d, nlist_d, nstat_d, wl_d);
```

### Description

`sosfil-cuda`: Cascaded IIR filter kernel [`sosfilt`](https://github.com/ORNL/HeCBench/blob/2f639b41e34d7adcab52f6cdcf23f77367ef2c5f/src/sosfil-cuda/main.cu#L38) has a read-write race on the shared `s_out` array.

Within each iteration of the systolic pipeline loop, thread `tx` reads `s_out[tx - 1]` (the previous iteration's value from the adjacent section) and thread `tx - 1` writes `s_out[tx - 1]` with the current iteration's value — both happen before `__syncthreads()`. When threads span different warps (blockDim = 64), the write may execute before the read, causing thread `tx` to use the wrong (current-iteration) value instead of the intended previous-iteration value.

### Reproduce

```bash
cd HeCBench/src/sosfil-cuda
make clean && make ARCH=sm_120
compute-sanitizer --tool=racecheck ./main 1
```

### Environment
- **CUDA version**: CUDA 13.1
- **GPU**: NVIDIA RTX 5070 Ti (sm_120)
- **OS**: Ubuntu 22.04

### Relevant Log Snippet

```
========= Error: Race reported between Read access at void sosfilt<float>(...)+0xb00
=========     and Write access at void sosfilt<float>(...)+0xbb0 [3780 hazards]
=========
========= Error: Race reported between Read access at void sosfilt<float>(...)+0xbd0
=========     and Write access at void sosfilt<float>(...)+0xce0 [3780 hazards]
=========
========= RACECHECK SUMMARY: 5 hazards displayed (5 errors, 0 warnings)
```

5 errors = 1 kernel × 3 phases (loading, processing, unloading) + 2 shared arrays (`s_out` for cascade output, `s_zi` state overlap).

### Root Cause

In `main.cu`, the [`sosfilt`](https://github.com/ORNL/HeCBench/blob/2f639b41e34d7adcab52f6cdcf23f77367ef2c5f/src/sosfil-cuda/main.cu#L38) kernel implements a cascaded second-order sections (SOS) IIR filter as a systolic pipeline. Each thread represents one filter section. In the loading phase ([lines 80-98](https://github.com/ORNL/HeCBench/blob/2f639b41e34d7adcab52f6cdcf23f77367ef2c5f/src/sosfil-cuda/main.cu#L80-L98)):

```cpp
for (int n = 0; n < load_size; n++) {
    if (tx == 0) {
        x_n = x_in[ty * n_samples + n];
    } else {
        x_n = s_out[tx - 1];  // READ: thread tx reads output of section tx-1
    }
    temp = s_sos[tx * sos_width + 0] * x_n + s_zi[tx * zi_width + 0];
    // ... update s_zi ...
    s_out[tx] = temp;  // WRITE: thread tx-1 writes s_out[tx-1] here
    __syncthreads();   // BUG: sync is AFTER both read and write
}
```

Thread `tx` reads `s_out[tx - 1]` while thread `tx - 1` writes `s_out[tx - 1]`, both in the same iteration, before `__syncthreads()`. The kernel launches with `blockDim = THREADS = 64` ([line 165](https://github.com/ORNL/HeCBench/blob/2f639b41e34d7adcab52f6cdcf23f77367ef2c5f/src/sosfil-cuda/main.cu#L165)), so thread 31 (warp 0) and thread 32 (warp 1) span the warp boundary. The same race occurs in the processing phase ([lines 101-123](https://github.com/ORNL/HeCBench/blob/2f639b41e34d7adcab52f6cdcf23f77367ef2c5f/src/sosfil-cuda/main.cu#L101-L123)) and unloading phase ([lines 126-146](https://github.com/ORNL/HeCBench/blob/2f639b41e34d7adcab52f6cdcf23f77367ef2c5f/src/sosfil-cuda/main.cu#L126-L146)).

### Suggested Fix

Read the cascade input into a register before the barrier, then write the output after:

```diff
@@ -80,13 +80,16 @@
     for ( int n = 0; n < load_size; n++ ) {
+      T x_n;
       if ( tx == 0 ) {
         x_n = x_in[ty * n_samples + n];
       } else {
         x_n = s_out[tx - 1];
       }
+      __syncthreads( );  // ensure all reads of s_out complete before writes

       temp = s_sos[tx * sos_width + 0] * x_n + s_zi[tx * zi_width + 0];
       // ... update s_zi ...
       s_out[tx] = temp;

       __syncthreads( );
     }
```

Apply the same pattern to the processing phase (line 105) and unloading phase (line 129): add `__syncthreads()` after reading `s_out[tx - 1]` and before writing `s_out[tx]`.
